91
00:04:29,760 --> 00:04:32,462
Sean: I tell you what. I'm grateful.

92
00:04:32,464 --> 00:04:34,841
Weren't for you, you've given
us the word that these chappies

93
00:04:34,866 --> 00:04:36,954
were running around with... with a cure,

94
00:04:36,979 --> 00:04:38,618
we wouldn't be on this side of the Atlantic

95
00:04:38,643 --> 00:04:39,617
for at least a month.

96
00:04:39,642 --> 00:04:41,117
Left out a key bit of information

97
00:04:41,142 --> 00:04:42,782
about the medical ship, though, didn't he?

98
00:04:42,807 --> 00:04:45,074
[Loudly] I already ex...

99
00:04:45,099 --> 00:04:46,782
Ned, I...

100
00:04:47,080 --> 00:04:49,482
I had absolutely no idea

101
00:04:49,507 --> 00:04:51,032
where the Navy ship was traveling.

102
00:04:51,057 --> 00:04:53,631
They left me to die in the Caribbean.

103
00:04:53,656 --> 00:04:55,516
Tell us more about that vessel.

104
00:04:55,697 --> 00:04:57,649
- <i>Nathan James?</i>
- Yeah.

105
00:04:57,680 --> 00:05:00,192
Not a large ship, but formidable.

106
00:05:00,217 --> 00:05:01,092
We know.

107
00:05:01,117 --> 00:05:03,293
- Bleedin' saw it.
- Ned.

108
00:05:03,739 --> 00:05:05,798
Niels: There's a doctor on board, a woman.

109
00:05:05,823 --> 00:05:08,023
She used all my research
to help develop the cure.

110
00:05:08,048 --> 00:05:10,496
Ain't interested in a doctor at the moment.

111
00:05:10,521 --> 00:05:13,155
Tell us about that ship. Who's the captain?

112
00:05:13,270 --> 00:05:15,604
Uh, his name's Chandler, he's like, uh...

113
00:05:15,629 --> 00:05:17,095
How do you say...

114
00:05:17,442 --> 00:05:19,571
A difficult fellow to come to terms with.

115
00:05:19,596 --> 00:05:22,860
He defeated the renowned
Russian Admiral Ruskov, twice.

116
00:05:22,885 --> 00:05:26,386
Shot the ship right out
from under me. Sunk it.

117
00:05:26,411 --> 00:05:29,112
You're lying. No, I wish I was.

118
00:05:29,137 --> 00:05:32,127
I mean, I barely escaped with my life.

119
00:05:32,152 --> 00:05:36,994
I stand before you the sole
survivor of this disaster.

120
00:05:37,019 --> 00:05:38,494
Ruskov's gone, eh?

121
00:05:38,519 --> 00:05:39,955
Ruskov's dead!

122
00:05:39,980 --> 00:05:41,525
- [Plays guitar riff]
- Rus... Ruskov's dead.

123
00:05:41,551 --> 00:05:43,393
- Nice one, mate! Nice one!
- Ruskov's dead, yeah?

124
00:05:43,418 --> 00:05:44,479
Well, that's a stroke of luck.

125
00:05:44,504 --> 00:05:47,438
You have to be careful
with this Chandler, okay?

126
00:05:48,020 --> 00:05:50,779
He's... Very resourceful.

127
00:05:50,804 --> 00:05:53,178
This here's a sub, all right?

128
00:05:53,203 --> 00:05:55,579
A Destroyer can't touch a sub.

129
00:05:55,604 --> 00:05:57,885
Piece of shit tin can
won't even see us coming.

130
00:05:57,910 --> 00:05:59,658
- [Scoffs]
- He's right.

131
00:05:59,683 --> 00:06:03,361
You picked the right horse this
time, Niels. Yeah, sit down.

132
00:06:06,729 --> 00:06:09,598
[Grunts]

133
00:06:17,768 --> 00:06:21,165
Water. Please.

134
00:06:21,509 --> 00:06:24,050
[Coughing]

135
00:06:24,075 --> 00:06:26,609
[Strained voice] I am sorry.

136
00:06:26,634 --> 00:06:29,589
One sip, then you start talkin'.

137
00:06:30,826 --> 00:06:32,360
Who are you?

138
00:06:32,639 --> 00:06:35,690
I am Juan Carlos DE Marquez Y Santamaria.

139
00:06:35,715 --> 00:06:38,349
DE la Fuerza DE Guerra
Especial, Spanish Royal Navy.

140
00:06:38,374 --> 00:06:39,940
And what vessel are you from?

141
00:06:40,126 --> 00:06:42,809
It is not Spanish, but I can tell you

142
00:06:42,834 --> 00:06:45,747
it is an <i>Astute</i> class
submarine from the British Navy.

143
00:06:46,050 --> 00:06:47,783
I do not know its name.

144
00:06:47,808 --> 00:06:49,274
You don't know the name of your own ship?

145
00:06:49,299 --> 00:06:51,671
I was a... How do you say?

146
00:06:51,928 --> 00:06:56,377
Drafted off the coast of
Cadiz only two weeks ago.

147
00:06:56,402 --> 00:06:57,218
[Coughs]

148
00:06:57,243 --> 00:06:58,642
Who's your commander?

149
00:06:58,667 --> 00:07:00,742
[Coughing]

150
00:07:00,890 --> 00:07:02,812
I'm sorry. Water.

151
00:07:02,837 --> 00:07:05,704
What's goin' on here,
doc? Is he milkin' this?

152
00:07:05,729 --> 00:07:07,996
He's just bruised, that's all.

153
00:07:08,021 --> 00:07:09,921
I took a blow here. [Sighs]

154
00:07:09,946 --> 00:07:14,315
One of your fighters.
They are very well-trained.

155
00:07:14,340 --> 00:07:15,839
Mm-hmm.

156
00:07:19,308 --> 00:07:20,842
Your commander.

157
00:07:20,867 --> 00:07:22,765
That's what they call him. "Commander."

158
00:07:22,790 --> 00:07:23,566
No name?

159
00:07:23,591 --> 00:07:26,515
He's a Brit and a maniac.

160
00:07:26,540 --> 00:07:27,873
That's all I know, sir.

161
00:07:27,898 --> 00:07:29,816
What were you doing on <i>Solace?</i>

162
00:07:31,182 --> 00:07:33,632
Looking for the cure,
like the rest of the world.

163
00:07:33,657 --> 00:07:35,493
You shot a hell of a lot of
people while you were lookin'.

164
00:07:35,517 --> 00:07:36,792
You must believe me.

165
00:07:36,817 --> 00:07:39,792
I did not know his men
were going to do this.

166
00:07:39,817 --> 00:07:41,569
We got on that ship, and suddenly

167
00:07:41,594 --> 00:07:44,069
they started killing
everyone for no reason.

168
00:07:44,234 --> 00:07:46,562
Commander's brother... he started it.

169
00:07:46,587 --> 00:07:49,463
Way I saw it, <i>you</i>
were shooting at my men.

170
00:07:49,487 --> 00:07:50,962
[Scoffs]

171
00:07:51,678 --> 00:07:54,679
They would have killed me if I hadn't, sir.

172
00:07:56,168 --> 00:07:58,762
<i>Dios mío,</i> this is an insane world.

173
00:07:58,787 --> 00:08:02,062
I thought I was joining with
this group for my own security,

174
00:08:02,087 --> 00:08:04,762
not to kill innocent civilians.

175
00:08:04,787 --> 00:08:05,843
Trust me.

176
00:08:05,868 --> 00:08:07,788
- Where's the sub now? Where'd he go?
- I don't...

177
00:08:07,813 --> 00:08:08,650
Is he looking for us?

178
00:08:09,598 --> 00:08:12,866
I think you would... you
would know better than me, sir.

179
00:08:17,554 --> 00:08:19,288
- Wait, wait, wait.
- [Chair thuds]

180
00:08:19,313 --> 00:08:22,014
I am sorry for what I did.

181
00:08:22,039 --> 00:08:25,173
I would understand if you
killed me right now, but...

182
00:08:25,198 --> 00:08:27,205
[Coughs]

183
00:08:27,640 --> 00:08:30,541
If you would give me the chance,

184
00:08:30,777 --> 00:08:35,647
sir, I feel much happier
here with you and your crew

185
00:08:35,672 --> 00:08:39,107
than with this lunatic criminal.

186
00:08:40,403 --> 00:08:43,106
I ask you now for political asylum.

187
00:08:43,131 --> 00:08:46,106
I will give you anything
you need that could help you,

188
00:08:46,131 --> 00:08:48,831
any information, I-I promise.

189
00:08:49,559 --> 00:08:51,322
Chandler: You believe him?

190
00:08:51,347 --> 00:08:52,934
What he's been saying squares with

191
00:08:52,959 --> 00:08:54,567
what Burk and Green saw
aboard <i>Solace,</i>

192
00:08:54,592 --> 00:08:55,848
and what I saw from the bridge wing,

193
00:08:55,873 --> 00:08:57,129
but I just want more on that sub.

194
00:08:57,154 --> 00:09:00,395
And we got our second
string A.S.W. Evaluator.

195
00:09:00,592 --> 00:09:02,418
- Mason can handle it.
- Oh.

196
00:09:02,702 --> 00:09:05,432
He knows the equipment. He
just doesn't have the hours.

197
00:09:05,457 --> 00:09:08,558
Jenkins spent his entire career
training for that one job.

198
00:09:08,583 --> 00:09:10,672
It was all he did all day long.

199
00:09:10,696 --> 00:09:11,723
Mason: All stations,

200
00:09:11,748 --> 00:09:13,788
sonar holds new passive contact, uh,

201
00:09:13,813 --> 00:09:16,247
approximate bearing 2-3-5.

202
00:09:16,272 --> 00:09:17,647
[Paper rustles]

203
00:09:17,672 --> 00:09:19,312
Sir, I'm hearing something now.

204
00:09:19,337 --> 00:09:21,663
It appears to be on the
edge of the convergence zone,

205
00:09:21,665 --> 00:09:24,715
but every couple minutes
I hear the faintest... Hum.

206
00:09:24,740 --> 00:09:26,086
What's the bearing?

207
00:09:26,111 --> 00:09:28,442
I believe it's between

208
00:09:28,467 --> 00:09:30,841
2-3-0 and 2-3-5 relative, sir.

209
00:09:30,989 --> 00:09:32,532
Is it the sub?

210
00:09:33,853 --> 00:09:36,541
I don't know, sir, but
it's running very quiet.

211
00:09:36,566 --> 00:09:38,666
Well, anything that
quiet has gotta be a sub.

212
00:09:38,691 --> 00:09:41,792
I agree, sir, but something this quiet...

213
00:09:41,817 --> 00:09:44,348
It... it must be a type 2-1-4.

214
00:09:44,373 --> 00:09:46,082
Juan Carlos said it was
an <i>Astute</i> class.

215
00:09:46,107 --> 00:09:47,698
I suppose that that's possible, sir,

216
00:09:47,723 --> 00:09:49,323
If it were fitted with
the new sound matting.

217
00:09:49,609 --> 00:09:51,375
That would make it <i>Ajax</i>
or <i>Achilles,</i>sir.

218
00:09:51,400 --> 00:09:52,614
<i>Ajax</i> was still being fitted.

219
00:09:52,639 --> 00:09:54,309
Then it's <i>Achilles,</i>sir.

220
00:09:55,981 --> 00:09:57,413
Where's it headed?

221
00:09:58,582 --> 00:10:01,183
I'm sorry, sir, I can't
tell. It's just too far out.

222
00:10:01,208 --> 00:10:02,224
Gator!

223
00:10:02,249 --> 00:10:04,649
We don't have a heading yet, sir.

224
00:10:10,665 --> 00:10:13,066
- Commander.
- Sean: What is it?

225
00:10:13,091 --> 00:10:16,356
It's, uh, a ship traveling south.

226
00:10:16,381 --> 00:10:19,578
Pitifully slow. 12
knots. It's not very big.

227
00:10:19,603 --> 00:10:22,675
Could be a-a freighter or a small tanker.

228
00:10:22,700 --> 00:10:24,614
It's underpowered. You
could barely hear its engine.

229
00:10:24,639 --> 00:10:26,034
- Are you having me on?
- No.

230
00:10:26,059 --> 00:10:28,151
Ain't no freighters doing
business during an apocalypse.

231
00:10:28,177 --> 00:10:30,589
That ship ain't going slow
'cause it's underpowered.

232
00:10:30,614 --> 00:10:32,352
It's going slow so's to be quiet.

233
00:10:32,377 --> 00:10:34,577
12 knots's standard speed for a destroyer

234
00:10:34,611 --> 00:10:35,886
traveling at quiet level one.

235
00:10:35,911 --> 00:10:37,175
That ain't no freighter.

236
00:10:37,200 --> 00:10:38,745
That there's the destroyer, mate.

237
00:10:38,832 --> 00:10:40,532
Calculate range and intercept.

238
00:10:40,557 --> 00:10:41,823
Calculating range, aye.

239
00:10:41,950 --> 00:10:43,446
Arm torpedoes.

240
00:10:43,471 --> 00:10:45,246
Arming torpedoes, aye.

241
00:10:53,869 --> 00:10:57,338
[Sonar pinging steadily]

242
00:10:59,740 --> 00:11:00,907
It's shallow where she is.

243
00:11:00,932 --> 00:11:02,198
I think I'm getting some kick

244
00:11:02,223 --> 00:11:03,658
from her prop off the sea bottom.

245
00:11:03,683 --> 00:11:05,857
How shallow?

246
00:11:07,141 --> 00:11:09,049
A guess, sir.

247
00:11:09,074 --> 00:11:11,330
I-I'd say 400 feet or less.

248
00:11:11,355 --> 00:11:13,022
Anybody else out there?

249
00:11:13,541 --> 00:11:16,000
I mean, I've got some biologics,
maybe 8, 10 miles south.

250
00:11:16,025 --> 00:11:17,959
Porpoises, maybe. Probably dolphins.

251
00:11:18,403 --> 00:11:21,068
Gate, if you follow
the bearing 2-3-5 out,

252
00:11:21,093 --> 00:11:22,496
where does it get that shallow?

253
00:11:22,521 --> 00:11:24,744
Uh, North end of the Bahama Bank,

254
00:11:24,769 --> 00:11:25,885
west of the islands, sir.

255
00:11:25,910 --> 00:11:27,142
That fit with what you're getting?

256
00:11:27,167 --> 00:11:30,142
Yes, sir. That would put
them roughly 50 miles out,

